Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} and half the @ginger puree{15%g} in a medium #saucepan{} (with a tight-fitting lid) on medium-high heat. Once hot, stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} until coated, ~{1%minute}, then add @salt{1/4%tsp} and the @water{300%ml} and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the #lid{}.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

== Curry ==

While the rice cooks, halve the @green pepper{1}(halved) and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @unconventional plant-based burgers{2} and sliced pepper to the pan and use a #spoon{} to mash the burgers a mince-like texture as it cooks. Cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. 

> IMPORTANT: Ensure they're piping hot throughout.

Add the garlic, @rogan josh curry paste{50%g} and remaining ginger puree to the plant-based mince. Stir-fry until fragrant, ~{1%minute}.

Next, stir in the @tomato passata{1%carton}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, @sugar{1%tsp} and @water{75%ml}.

Bring to the boil and simmer until thickened, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Taste and add @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if needed.

== To Serve ==

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and share between your #bowls{}. Top with the plant-based mince curry.

Finish with a dollop of @greek style natural yoghurt{75%g} and @chilli flakes{1%pinch} (use less if you'd prefer things milder).

Enjoy!